9fa80fee6640"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "But what if we want to move an operator from the bra to the ket without \
switching the operators? For that, we need to define something called the \
adjoint. In the case of a matrix, the adjoint is just another name for the \
conjugate transpose (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["A",
     FontWeight->"Bold",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], 
    StyleBox["H",
     FontWeight->"Bold",
     FontSlant->"Plain"]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9264202b-cdfc-41a1-a602-a7c63967d56e"],
 "), but let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s define the adjoint of an operator ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["A",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], "\[Dagger]"]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8113265575394135`*^9, 3.8113266208341584`*^9}, {
    3.8113268886705112`*^9, 3.8113269031313066`*^9}, 3.8113270406173744`*^9, {
    3.811330598918048*^9, 3.8113306162990384`*^9}, {3.811330646381595*^9, 
    3.8113306467325897`*^9}, {3.811330739744603*^9, 3.8113307427314014`*^9}, {
